On the other hand, Soviet experts didn't value the importance of Chinese architecture. They thought that, as the capital city of China, Beijing would need to be the center of the nation. It needed to have a place like the Red Square in Moscow, so the supreme leader could meet his people and wave to them. [p]
They also thought the labor population in Beijing was too low, so Beijing needed to develop their industry. Meanwhile, Beijing should also be the center of politics, economy, culture, and education. [p]

[_tb_end_text]

[chara_show  name="LiangSicheng"  time="1000"  wait="true"  left="193"  top="13"  width="463"  height="611"  reflect="false"  ]
[tb_start_text mode=1 ]
Liang Sicheng totally disagreed with the Soviet Proposal; he believed Beijing could preserve the old city layout and develop a new city center at the same time. The Tiananmen Square could still be the national symbol of China even though the central government was built on western Beijing. [p]
Liang also didn't allow Beijing to become the center of "Everything", because it would occupy a lot of resources, causing traffic problems and overpopulation in the future. [p]
He believed the "Liang-Chen Proposal" would be a more sustainable solution for Beijing. [p]

[_tb_end_text]

